				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/boa-noah" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1340953); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1340953&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252642" alt="Boa Noah" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1340953)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/boa-noah" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1340953); return false;" >Boa Noah</a></span> <span class="odate time_1338350466 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 May 2012 04:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1463990">
									

<p>Yes, crocodiles are a good example of a predator that utilizes both water and land for hunting, however a crocodile isn't a massive aquatic predator. A better reference in regards to this thing would be a killer whale since they are massive aquatic predators and they can temporarily go on shore to attack prey (though they must be careful when doing so as they can easily beach themselves.)</p>
<p>However it still doesn't make sense, why would it get impatient? Why would it handicap itself when it can just wait? Why can it interact with any liquid when it's primary hunting ground/feeding ground is in the ocean?</p>
<p>*I don't know&#8230;</p>

